    "Ethanol acts primarily as a central nervous system (CNS) depressant by enhancing gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) activity at GABA-A receptors and inhibiting glutamate activity at NMDA receptors. Chronic alcohol exposure leads to neuroadaptation: GABA receptors become downregulated while NMDA receptors are upregulated, producing tolerance and physical dependence. Alcohol also increases dopamine release in the nucleus accumbens, reinforcing drinking behavior. The enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase converts ethanol to acetaldehyde, which is then metabolized by aldehyde dehydrogenase to acetate.",
