    "Behavioral signs include drinking more or longer than intended, unsuccessful attempts to cut down, spending significant time obtaining or recovering from alcohol, craving alcohol, continued use despite social or interpersonal problems, tolerance (needing more to achieve the same effect), and withdrawal symptoms upon cessation. Physical signs of chronic use include hepatomegaly, spider angiomata, palmar erythema, tremors, peripheral neuropathy, and Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome. Withdrawal symptoms range from mild anxiety and tremors (6–24 hours) to seizures (24–48 hours) and delirium tremens (48–72 hours).",
