    "Opioids bind to mu, kappa, and delta opioid receptors throughout the central and peripheral nervous systems. Activation of mu receptors produces analgesia, euphoria, respiratory depression, and physical dependence. Chronic opioid exposure leads to receptor downregulation, requiring increasingly higher doses to achieve the same effect (tolerance). Upon cessation, the absence of opioid receptor activation produces withdrawal symptoms as the nervous system rebalances. Fentanyl is 50–100 times more potent than morphine, contributing to its disproportionate role in overdose deaths.",
